<!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
<div id="lp-how" style="display:none">
  <div class="l-wrap-sm">
    <p class="l-sec-label">How it works</p>
    <h2 class="l-sec-h2">How Groundwork works.</h2>
    <p class="l-sec-p">Every Ground follows the same simple path, from a clear beginning to a clear end.</p>
    <div style="margin-bottom:40px">
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">1</div><div><div class="l-step-title">Start a Ground</div><div class="l-step-desc">Start one for an important piece of work where expectations, responsibilities, or delivery are easy to lose track of, or when something already underway does not feel right. You do not have to start at the very beginning. The manager sets the starting point: the objectives, what success looks like, expectations, responsibilities, constraints, and the context that matters. This becomes the baseline the rest of the Ground is measured against.</div></div></div>
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">2</div><div><div class="l-step-title">Invite the people involved</div><div class="l-step-desc">Invite everyone involved: managers, employees, partners, and stakeholders. Everyone checks in on their own so every person gets the same chance to contribute, regardless of confidence, personality, communication style, or seniority.</div></div></div>
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">3</div><div><div class="l-step-title">What stays private, what is shared</div><div class="l-step-desc">Your check-in stays private to you. Groundwork uses everyone's responses to build the shared report, which shows where people agree, where they understand things differently, and what needs attention. It never shows anyone's raw answers, and it never identifies who said what about another person. The shared report appears once everyone has checked in. This is what makes people comfortable being honest, which is what makes the Ground worth having.</div></div></div>
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">4</div><div><div class="l-step-title">Check in as the work goes on</div><div class="l-step-desc">Groundwork runs regular check-ins and prompts people automatically when it is their turn, so you are not left chasing anyone. Each one records where things stand: progress, priorities, changes, commitments, risks, concerns, and any evidence. A check-in takes about ten minutes.</div></div></div>
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">5</div><div><div class="l-step-title">Groundwork compares the whole picture</div><div class="l-step-desc">At every check-in, Groundwork compares what people are saying now with what was agreed at the beginning, what they said before, and the evidence they have provided. It shows the things that are hard to see through meetings and documents alone: expectations that have changed, risks starting to show, work falling behind, unclear ownership, and where a conversation is needed. Example: "Two people described different agreed deadlines. Shown at check-in 2, before the deadline passed."</div></div></div>
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">6</div><div><div class="l-step-title">Read the reports, and take them into your calls</div><div class="l-step-desc">Managers get reports showing progress against the objectives, what has changed, risks, where expectations differ, delivery against commitments, and the conversations worth having now. Groundwork does not replace your one-to-ones. Take the report into them, so the meeting is spent on the conversation, not the catch-up.</div></div></div>
      <div class="l-step"><div class="l-step-num">7</div><div><div class="l-step-title">Close the Ground</div><div class="l-step-desc">When the work reaches its end, Groundwork compares the final outcome with the starting point and produces a clear conclusion: objectives against what was delivered, how expectations changed, the key decisions, the evidence, what was learned, and the complete history of the Ground. Every Ground gives the next manager, team, or project a clearer place to start.</div></div></div>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#F5F3EF;border-radius:10px;padding:24px;border-left:3px solid #0C447C;margin-bottom:32px">
      <h3 style="font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:8px">Alignment status</h3>
      <p style="font-size:13px;color:#6B6560;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:16px">Every report carries a clear read on where things stand. It is not a grade out of five. It is a plain summary of how many areas are aligned, how many are partly there, and how many are still open, so you can always see exactly what it is based on.</p>
      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(5,1fr);gap:8px">
        <div style="text-align:center;padding:10px 6px;background:white;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #E2E0DB"><div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#8A5C1A">Unresolved</div><div style="font-size:10px;color:#B4B2A9;margin-top:3px">Little common ground yet</div></div>
        <div style="text-align:center;padding:10px 6px;background:white;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #E2E0DB"><div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#9B9590">Mixed</div><div style="font-size:10px;color:#B4B2A9;margin-top:3px">Some aligned, several open</div></div>
        <div style="text-align:center;padding:10px 6px;background:white;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #E2E0DB"><div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#0C447C">Emerging</div><div style="font-size:10px;color:#B4B2A9;margin-top:3px">Alignment forming</div></div>
        <div style="text-align:center;padding:10px 6px;background:white;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #E2E0DB"><div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#0C447C">Clear</div><div style="font-size:10px;color:#B4B2A9;margin-top:3px">Substance settled</div></div>
        <div style="text-align:center;padding:10px 6px;background:#085041;border-radius:6px"><div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:white">Aligned</div><div style="font-size:10px;color:rgba(255,255,255,.6);margin-top:3px">Agreed and on the same page</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#EEF4FB;border:1px solid #B5D4F4;border-radius:10px;padding:16px 20px;margin-bottom:32px">
      <p style="font-size:13px;color:#0C447C;line-height:1.7;margin:0"><b>Groundwork supports the manager, it does not replace them.</b> It does not decide who was right or evaluate personalities and communication styles. It helps managers understand what happened, what has changed, and where a conversation is needed. Managers still make the decisions.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="text-align:center">
      <a class="l-btn-solid" style="padding:13px 28px;font-size:14px" href={`${APP_URL}/start`}>Start your first Ground</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- USE CASES -->
<div id="lp-usecases" style="display:none">
  <div class="l-wrap-sm">
    <p class="l-sec-label">Use cases</p>
    <h2 class="l-sec-h2">Where Groundwork earns its place.</h2>
    <p class="l-sec-p">The shape is the same every time. Each person gives their own account, independently. Groundwork shows where they match, where they differ, and what to do about it. Here is what that looks like across the moments it helps most.</p>

    <h3 style="font-size:13px;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#9B9590;font-weight:700;margin:28px 0 14px">Starting something</h3>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">New hire</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">A new hire and their manager each describe what success looks like in the first ninety days, independently. Groundwork shows where the two pictures match and where they quietly differ, before month three turns a small gap into a hard review conversation.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">New project</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Everyone joining a new project sets out scope, ownership, and what done looks like, on their own. Groundwork surfaces the assumptions that do not line up, so the project starts on agreed ground rather than discovering the mismatch at delivery.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">New board member or advisor</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">A new board member and the team each set out what the role is for and what good looks like. Groundwork shows where expectations diverge, so the relationship is defined before it starts costing more than it returns.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">New partner or cofounder</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Each founder records their own account of roles, contribution, and what success means. Groundwork shows where they agree and where they differ, so equity and authority rest on something written, not on memory.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Contract renewal</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Both sides of a contract describe what was delivered against what was expected, independently. Groundwork builds the record the renewal or exit decision rests on, rather than leaving it to relationship management.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">New direction</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Before a pivot, each person sets out the goals, responsibilities, and risks as they see them. Groundwork surfaces where the new direction is understood differently, so the team commits to the same plan.</p></div>

    <h3 style="font-size:13px;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#9B9590;font-weight:700;margin:32px 0 14px">Recognition</h3>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Asking for a raise</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The person and their manager each account for what was contributed over the period, independently. Groundwork builds the case from a record made over time, not assembled the night before the conversation.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Promotion or role change</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Both sides describe the scope and impact of the role as it ran. Groundwork shows where the accounts agree, so the case is built from the record rather than from who argues best in the moment.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Equity negotiation</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Each party documents contribution and expectation before the negotiation. Groundwork puts both accounts side by side, so the conversation starts from a shared picture instead of two competing memories.</p></div>

    <h3 style="font-size:13px;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#9B9590;font-weight:700;margin:32px 0 14px">When performance expectations need to be on record</h3>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Performance improvement</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Before a PIP is issued, the manager and the person each set out what good performance looks like and where the gaps are, independently. Groundwork shows where expectations match and where they don't, so the conversation starts from a shared picture rather than a surprise. The record is there from the beginning, not assembled after things have already gone wrong.</p></div>

    <h3 style="font-size:13px;letter-spacing:.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#9B9590;font-weight:700;margin:32px 0 14px">When you need everyone seeing the same thing</h3>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Team realignment</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Each person checks in on where the team is and what matters most, independently. Groundwork shows where people are pulling in different directions without realising it, so the team can reset to one outcome.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Multi-stakeholder programme</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Teams, partners, funders, and implementers each give their own account, with no one seeing the others. Groundwork builds one shared picture across all of them, so a programme with many parties moves on the same facts.</p></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid #E2E0DB;border-radius:10px;padding:18px 20px;margin-bottom:12px;background:#fff"><div style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:#1A1916;margin-bottom:6px">Progress review</div><p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#4A5568;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Everyone records what was agreed, what was delivered, and what should happen next. Groundwork shows where those accounts line up and where they do not, so the review produces decisions rather than debate.</p></div>

    <div style="text-align:center;margin-top:32px">
      <a class="l-btn-solid" style="padding:13px 28px;font-size:14px" href={`${APP_URL}/start`}>Start a Ground</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

